{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Adrian Beria Blog","author":"Adrian Beria"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"61073a88-fa99-5e08-a825-cbb2e72eb40a","excerpt":"React Context API  is a way to declare a global state to make it available for multiple components. The main reason this is used is to avoid…","html":"<p><a href=\"https://reactjs.org/docs/context.html\">React Context API</a> is a way to declare a global state to make it available for multiple components. The main reason this is used is to avoid what’s known as prop drilling, which means if we have a Grandparent (GP), Parent (P) and a Grandchild (GC), we normally would have to send information from GP->P->GC, so what’s wrong about this approach?</p>\n<ol>\n<li>We write more code because we would need to declare the props inside propTypes (it lets other devs know the type of data the props are).</li>\n<li>For a highly reusable component, adding too many props can overload it making it messy codewise.</li>\n<li>What happens if we instead of going through one parent, it goes through four? Yes, you add unnecesary code.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>So in conclusion, use React Context to avoid prop drilling.</p>\n<h2>Is React Context an alternative to Redux?</h2>\n<p>It depends on what you’re trying to accomplish, if its communicating simple values from child to parent or between siblings, you can use Context with callback functions (we will see this in another post) to communicate from child to parent or if its between siblings, you use it normally.</p>\n<p>But Redux has a lot of advantages which include less code overall because you follow the DRY principle. If we don’t use Redux in an app where we have to do a CRUD, we would need to use local state to know when the app is loading, when it gives an error or when its successful, do you imagine repeating this for 10 components? When we can just import an Action Creator that let us do the simple fetch and let the reducer handle the loading, error and successful events.</p>\n<p>In conclusion, its not an alternative to Redux in cases where we need Redux. Use it mostly to avoid prop drilling.</p>\n<h2>Grandparent to grandchild</h2>\n<p>For a quick example we create a context.js file which we use to create our context and add an initial value (similar to state), we export the Provider of the value and Context (used by the GC).</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/3a89373b62b019763710f0f4dee7e7cb/a4caf/context-tw-1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 477px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 35.84905660377359%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"code\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/3a89373b62b019763710f0f4dee7e7cb/a4caf/context-tw-1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3a89373b62b019763710f0f4dee7e7cb/a2316/context-tw-1.png 148w,\n/static/3a89373b62b019763710f0f4dee7e7cb/8f18d/context-tw-1.png 295w,\n/static/3a89373b62b019763710f0f4dee7e7cb/a4caf/context-tw-1.png 477w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 477px) 100vw, 477px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>In our GP component we import the Provider and surround the component, then we send the information we want to the grandchild through the value property</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/f8e84a77e012f7b309aefd56fb9d7029/346f0/context-tw-2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 586px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 56.8259385665529%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"code\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/f8e84a77e012f7b309aefd56fb9d7029/346f0/context-tw-2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f8e84a77e012f7b309aefd56fb9d7029/2834f/context-tw-2.png 148w,\n/static/f8e84a77e012f7b309aefd56fb9d7029/39b60/context-tw-2.png 295w,\n/static/f8e84a77e012f7b309aefd56fb9d7029/346f0/context-tw-2.png 586w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 586px) 100vw, 586px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>Now we can ignore the parent and go to the GC, we import the Context from our context.js file. We use “useContext” to get the value from our GP and use it however we want! We avoid prop drilling and declaring propTypes as well for parent</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/9f8ded866c0980e1bef1eb1952dd275b/1e685/context-tw-3.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 510px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 51.17647058823529%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"code\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/9f8ded866c0980e1bef1eb1952dd275b/1e685/context-tw-3.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/9f8ded866c0980e1bef1eb1952dd275b/9b682/context-tw-3.png 148w,\n/static/9f8ded866c0980e1bef1eb1952dd275b/ef5d6/context-tw-3.png 295w,\n/static/9f8ded866c0980e1bef1eb1952dd275b/1e685/context-tw-3.png 510w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 510px) 100vw, 510px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h2>Grandchild to Grandparent</h2>\n<p>We will use the callback functions to communicate between Grandchild and Grandparent using React Context, note that this can be done without Context, but if there is a case where you need to communicate child to a higher component in the tree, then use Context for this since its very easy to do and its less code than if we would do it with Redux.</p>\n<p>The idea is that you send a function as a prop which recieves the value from the child and reflects it on the parent, lets see this in action.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/91a097d857e97b6858de465d6108e745/fca27/context-tw-4.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 52.38805970149254%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"code\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/91a097d857e97b6858de465d6108e745/fb8a0/context-tw-4.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/91a097d857e97b6858de465d6108e745/1a291/context-tw-4.png 148w,\n/static/91a097d857e97b6858de465d6108e745/2bc4a/context-tw-4.png 295w,\n/static/91a097d857e97b6858de465d6108e745/fb8a0/context-tw-4.png 590w,\n/static/91a097d857e97b6858de465d6108e745/fca27/context-tw-4.png 670w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>As you can see the callback function takes a value as parameter and we set it on the state. Lets check how it looks on the child.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/4e45122108e1b22d8c9b487d29d73cb6/df86e/context-tw-5.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 41.00467289719626%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"code\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/4e45122108e1b22d8c9b487d29d73cb6/fb8a0/context-tw-5.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4e45122108e1b22d8c9b487d29d73cb6/1a291/context-tw-5.png 148w,\n/static/4e45122108e1b22d8c9b487d29d73cb6/2bc4a/context-tw-5.png 295w,\n/static/4e45122108e1b22d8c9b487d29d73cb6/fb8a0/context-tw-5.png 590w,\n/static/4e45122108e1b22d8c9b487d29d73cb6/df86e/context-tw-5.png 856w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>In this case when we write anything in the input we get the value reflected on the Grandparent component to use it however we like.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>We got to learn about React Context, a very useful tool to avoid prop drilling multiple components to send information, we got to see two common cases of a Grandparent to Grandchild and Grandchild to Grandparent.</p>\n<p>See you on the next post.</p>\n<p>Sincerely,</p>\n<p><strong>Eng Adrian Beria.</strong></p>","frontmatter":{"title":"React Context","date":"February 18, 2020"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/8-react-context/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/8-third-project-redux/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Third Project - Redux - Part 1 Fetch"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/11-third-project-redux-part-2/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Third Project - Redux - Part 2 Searchbar and Modal"}}}}